  • Use unnest_tokens() and unnest_ngrams() to extract tokens and ngrams from text.

  • Use dplyr and ggplot2 to analyze text data

  • Tokenize the the words in the transcription column
  • Count the number of times each token appears

  • Visualize the top 20 most frequent words
mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, transcription) %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE)  %>%
  top_n(20, n)  %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(word, n))) +
  geom_col(color = 'black', fill = viridis::magma(20)) +
  labs(title = "Top 20 Frequent Words from 'Transcription' Column",
       x = "Count",
       y = "Word")

Explain what we see from this result. Does it makes sense? What insights (if any) do we get?{.underline}

We see that the majority of words are âtheâ, âandâ, âwasâ. Knowing that weâre talking about medical records, the only word related is âPatientâ about halfway down the records. This visualization does not give us much insight and further breakdown of the words is necessary to see anything in the data.

Question 3

  • Redo visualization but remove stopwords before
  • Bonus points if you remove numbers as well
mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, transcription) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = c("word")) %>%
  filter(!stringr::str_detect(word, "^[0-9]+$")) %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(20, n) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(word, n))) +
  geom_col(color = 'black', fill = viridis::mako(20)) +
  labs(title = "Top 20 Frequent Words After Removing Stop Words and Numbers",
       x = "Count",
       y = "Word")

What do we see know that we have removed stop words? Does it give us a better idea of what the text is about?{.underline}

Once removing stop words and numbers, we can get a much bettwe idea about the text. From these words, we can see that it is healthcare/medical related.

       x = "Count",
       y = "Bi-Grams")

The most common bi-gram was âthe patientâ with over 20k mentions. There are many stop words within these results, which makes getting meaningful results from the graph, with the second most common bi-gram being âof theâ and âin theâ.

How does the result change if you look at tri-grams?{.underline}

mt_samples %>%
  unnest_ngrams(ngram, transcription, n = 3) %>%
  count(ngram, sort = TRUE) %>%
  slice_max( n, n = 20, with_ties = FALSE)  %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, fct_reorder(ngram, n))) +
  geom_col(color = 'black', fill = viridis::plasma(20)) +
  labs(title = "Top 20 Frequent Tri-Grams from 'Transcription' Column",
       x = "Count",
       y = "Tri-Grams")

The tri-grams show many less combinations than the bi-grams, but the top 20 give more insight than the bigrams. The top tri-gram was âthe patient wasâ, and many of these combinations seem more meaningful/have more medical language in them which can help us understand the text easier.

Question 6

Which words are most used in each of the specialties. you can use group_by() and top_n() from dplyr to have the calculations be done within each specialty. Remember to remove stopwords. How about the most 5 used words?{.underline}

mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, transcription) %>%
  group_by(medical_specialty) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = c("word")) %>%
  filter(!stringr::str_detect(word, "^[0-9]+$")) %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(5, n) %>%
  arrange(medical_specialty, desc(n))
